## \f1\u-10179?\u-8937?\f0  Understanding GitHub + Netlify Setup\par
\par
### How They Work Together:\par
\par
**Netlify** = Hosts your WEBSITE (HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images)\par
- This is what users see and interact with\par
- Your URL: `kamaro.netlify.app` (or custom domain)\par
- Free hosting, fast loading\par
\par
**GitHub** = Stores your APK FILES (the actual .apk downloads)\par
- This is where the downloadable files live\par
- Provides direct download links\par
- Free storage for your APKs\par
\par
### The Flow:\par
```\par
User visits kamaro.netlify.app (Netlify)\par
    \f3\u8595?\f0\par
User browses apps on your website\par
    \f3\u8595?\f0\par
User clicks "Download App" button\par
    \f3\u8595?\f0\par
Link redirects to GitHub\par
    \f3\u8595?\f0\par
APK downloads from GitHub to user's device\par
```\par
\par
Your website is the "storefront" - it displays apps beautifully, but the actual APK files are stored separately on GitHub.\par
\par
## \f1\u-10179?\u-8988?\f0  How to Upload APKs to GitHub (Step-by-Step)\par
\par
### Initial Setup (One-Time):\par
\par
1. **Create GitHub Account**\par
   - Go to github.com\par
   - Sign up (100% free)\par
   - Verify your email\par
\par
2. **Create Your APK Repository**\par
   - Click green "New" button (or "+" \f3\u8594?\f0  "New repository")\par
   - Repository name: `kamaro-apks` (or any name you prefer)\par
   - Description: "APK files for KAMARO app distribution"\par
   - Choose "Public" (so download links work)\par
   - Click "Create repository"\par
\par
### Method 1: Simple Upload (No Git Knowledge Required!)\par
\par
**For APKs under 100MB:**\par
\par
1. **Go to your repository** (`github.com/yourusername/kamaro-apks`)\par
\par
2. **Upload APK:**\par
   - Click "Add file" \f3\u8594?\f0  "Upload files"\par
   - Drag your .apk file OR click "choose your files"\par
   - Add commit message: "Add [AppName] v1.0"\par
   - Click "Commit changes"\par
\par
3. **Get Download Link:**\par
   - Click on the uploaded APK filename\par
   - Click "Download" button (right side of page)\par
   - Right-click on "Download" \f3\u8594?\f0  "Copy link address"\par
   - Your link looks like: `https://github.com/username/kamaro-apks/raw/main/myapp.apk`\par
\par
4. **Use This Link:**\par
   - Paste this URL into your website's `app-data.json` file\par
   - This is what users will download\par
\par
### Method 2: GitHub Releases (For APKs over 100MB)\par
\par
**For larger files (100MB - 2GB):**\par
\par
1. **Go to your repository**\par
\par
2. **Create a Release:**\par
   - Click "Releases" (right sidebar)\par
   - Click "Create a new release"\par
   - Tag version: `v1.0` (or your version number)\par
   - Release title: "AppName v1.0"\par
   - Description: Brief changelog or features\par
\par
3. **Attach APK:**\par
   - Scroll to "Attach binaries"\par
   - Drag your .apk file or click to upload\par
   - Click "Publish release"\par
\par
4. **Get Download Link:**\par
   - Find your release in the Releases section\par
   - Right-click on the APK filename \f3\u8594?\f0  "Copy link address"\par
   - Link looks like: `https://github.com/username/kamaro-apks/releases/download/v1.0/myapp.apk`\par
\par
### Organizing Your APKs on GitHub:\par
\par
**Recommended Structure:**\par
```\par
kamaro-apks/\par
\f2\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  app1.apk\par
